{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox company |name = Dialog Semiconductor PLC |logo = Dialog Semiconductor logo.svg |type = [[Public limited company]] ({{FWB|DLG}}) |foundation = 1981 |location = [[Reading, United Kingdom]] <small>(operational)</small>, [[London]], [[United Kingdom]] <small>([[registered office]])</small> |locations = |key_people = Richard Beyer <small>([[Chairman]])</small>, Jalal Bagherli <small>([[chief executive officer|CEO]])</small> |area_served = |industry = [[Electrical engineering]] |products = [[Semiconductor]]s, [[integrated circuit]]s |services = |revenue = {{Increase}} US$ 1,156.1&nbsp;million <small>(2014)</small><ref name="FS2014">{{cite web |url=http://www.dialog-semiconductor.com/docs/investor/2008_2014-financial-statements.pdf |title=Key Financial Statements 2008-2014 |publisher=Dialog Semiconductor |accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref> |operating_income = {{Increase}} US$ 185.9&nbsp;million <small>(2014)</small><ref name="FS2014" /> |net_income = {{Increase}} US$ 138.1&nbsp;million <small>(2014)</small><ref name="FS2014" /> |assets = {{Increase}} US$ 1,005.9&nbsp;million <small>(2014)</small><ref name="FS2014" /> |equity = {{Increase}} US$ 623.6&nbsp;million <small>(2014)</small><ref name="FS2014" /> |num_employees = 1500 <small>(July 2015)</small><ref name="SQ2015">{{cite web |url=http://www.dialog-semiconductor.com/docs/investor/q2_2015_results_en.pdf |title=second quarter results 2015 |publisher=Dialog Semiconductor |accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref> |parent = |divisions = |subsid = |homepage = {{URL|www.dialog-semiconductor.com}} }}
'''Dialog Semiconductor PLC''' is a [[UK]]-based manufacturer of [[semiconductor]] based system [[solution]]s. The company is headquartered in the [[United Kingdom]] in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]], with a global sales, R&D and marketing organization. Dialog creates highly integrated standard (ASSP) and custom (ASIC) mixed-signal integrated circuits (ICs), optimised for smartphone, computing, IoT, LED Solid State Lighting (SSL) and smart home applications. Dialog operates a [[fabless]] business model, but maintains its own test and physical laboratories at its office in Kirchheim.<ref>[http://www.dialog-semiconductor.de/lab.php dialog-semiconductor.de]</ref>
In 2015, it had approximately $1.35 billion in revenue and was one of the fastest growing European public semiconductor companies. It currently has approximately 1,650 employees worldwide. The company is listed on the Frankfurt (FWB: DLG) stock exchange (Regulated Market, Prime Standard, ISIN GB0059822006) and is a member of the German TecDax index.
On 10 February 2011, Dialog announced that it had completed a transaction to acquire SiTel Semiconductor B.V.<ref>[http://www.eetimes.com/electronics-news/4213031/Dialog-buys-wireless--VoIP-chip-firm- Dialog buys wireless, VoIP chip firm]</ref> ("SiTel"), a short-range wireless, digital cordless and VoIP technology company. In July 2013, Dialog announced that it has completed a transaction to acquire iWatt, an AC/DC power conversion and solid state lighting technologies company.{{cn|date=September 2018}}
Dialog Semiconductor is the exclusive designer of [[power management integrated circuit|power management integrated circuits]] (PMICs) for the Apple iPhone, iPad, and Watch, which made up more than 70% of Dialog’s 2016 sales. Its share value halved from April to December 2017 after private bank [[Bankhaus Lampe]] changed its outlook for the company from “hold” to “sell” in the belief Apple would replace Dialog’s PMIC designs with its own, predicting in-house design would be part of a general strategic shift for Dialog’s main client: Apple had established its own PMIC design centres in Munich and California, and in April 2017, Apple graphics chip maker [[Imagination Technologies]] declared that Apple would be designing its graphics chips in-house by 2020.<ref>{{ cite web | title=Apple may ditch Dialog, analyst says, hitting chipmaker's shares | last=Auchard | first=Eric | last2=Wolde | first2=Harro Ten | website=Reuters | date=2017-04-12 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-dialog-apple/apple-may-ditch-dialog-analyst-says-hitting-chipmakers-shares-idUSKBN17D0VF | access-date=2018-08-12 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite web | title=Apple to design power chips in-house as early as 2018: Sources | last=Ting-Fang | first=Cheng | website=Nikkei Asian Review | date=2017-11-30 | url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Business/Companies/Apple-to-design-power-chips-in-house-as-early-as-2018-Sources | access-date=2018-08-12 }}</ref> ==History== Dialog Semiconductor originated from the European operations of International Microelectronic Products, Inc. – a Silicon Valley company founded in 1981 *1989 – Dialog Semiconductor formed as part of [[Messerschmitt-Bölkow-Blohm]] (part of Daimler-Benz) *March 1998 – Roland Pudelko appointed to CEO *1999 – Dialog Semiconductor plc formed, launched on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange *October 2005 – Jalal Bagherli appointed to CEO, replacing Roland Pudelko *February 2007 – Opens audio / power management R&D design centre in Edinburgh *November 2008 – Wins NMI Award for SmartXtend PMOLED display driver technology *February 2009 – Launches world’s first configurable power management IC{{cn|date=September 2018}} *September 2009 – Relocates to new Swindon facility *October 2009 – Launches company’s first standalone audio codec *December 2010 – Launches world’s first 2D-3D image conversion IC for portable devices, wins GSA’s EMEA Leadership Council Award *January 2011 – Opens larger Edinburgh audio / power management R&D design facility *February 2011 – Acquires SiTel Semiconductor B.V. *December 2012 – New Design Centers in Livorno, Italy and Istanbul, Turkey *July 2013 – Acquires [http://iwatt.com/ iWatt Inc.] <ref>http://www.dialog-semiconductor.com/docs/investor/iwatt-acquisition-press-release.pdf</ref> *December 2014 — New Design Center in Chandler, Arizona *September 2015 – Announces agreement to acquire [[Atmel]].<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/09/20/us-atmel-m-a-dialog-idUSKCN0RK0J420150920 Dialog Semiconductor to buy U.S. peer Atmel for $4.6 billion; Reuters; September 20, 2015.]</ref> This agreement was cancelled in January 2016 when Atmel agreed to be purchased by [[Microchip Technology|Microchip]] instead. To break the agreement, Atmel paid Dialog a termination fee of $137.3 million.<ref name="marketwatch">{{Cite web|title = Microchip Technology buys chip maker Atmel in $3.56 billion deal|url = http://www.marketwatch.com/story/microchip-technology-buys-chip-maker-atmel-in-356-billion-deal-2016-01-19|website = MarketWatch|access-date = 2016-01-21|first = Claudia|last = Assis}}</ref> *November 2016 – Announces strategic partnership and $10 million investment with Energous Corporation <ref>[http://www.dialog-semiconductor.com/press-releases/dialog-semiconductor-announces-strategic-partnership-and-investment-energous Dialog Semiconductor Announces Strategic Partnership and Investment with Energous Corporation to Accelerate Wireless Charging Adoption]</ref> *October 2017 - Announces acquisition of Silego Technology<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dialog-semiconductor.com/dialog-semiconductor-acquire-silego-technology-leader-configurable-mixed-signal-ics|title=Dialog Semiconductor to Acquire Silego Technology, the Leader in Configurable Mixed-Signal ICs|last=lauren.ofstedahl@diasemi.com|date=2017-10-05|work=Dialog Semiconductor|access-date=2018-08-12|language=en}}</ref>
