{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}} {{Infobox company | name = Wincor Nixdorf AG | logo = Wincor Nixdorf.svg | logo_size = 175px | type = [[Aktiengesellschaft]] | traded_as = | foundation = 1952 | location = [[Paderborn]], [[Ostwestfalen-Lippe]], Germany | key_people = Eckard Heidloff <small>(President and CEO)</small>, Alexander Dibelius <small>(Chairman of the [[supervisory board]])</small> | industry = Information technology | products = Computer hardware, [[Computer software|software]], [[IT Service Management|IT services]] and [[Consultant|consulting]] for [[Branch (banking)|bank branches]] and retail stores; including [[Automated teller machine|ATM]]s and [[Point of sale|electronic point of sale]] systems | revenue = €2.427 billion <small>(2014/2015)</small><ref name="AR2014-15a">{{cite web |url=http://www.wincor-nixdorf.com/static/finanzberichte/2014-2015/q4/en/group-accounts/income-statement.html |title=Annual Report 2014/15 |accessdate=May 30, 2016 |publisher=Wincor Nixdorf}}</ref> | operating_income = €21.851 million <small>(2014/2015)</small><ref name="AR2014-15a" /> | net_income = €7.772 million <small>(2014/2015)</small><ref name="AR2014-15a" /> | assets = €1.507 billion <small>(September 2015)</small><ref name="AR2014-15b">{{cite web |url=http://www.wincor-nixdorf.com/static/finanzberichte/2014-2015/q4/en/group-accounts/balance-sheet.html |title=Annual Report 2014/15 |accessdate=May 30, 2016 |publisher=Wincor Nixdorf}}</ref> | equity = €391.440 million <small>(September 2015)</small><ref name="AR2014-15b" /> | num_employees = 9,100 <small>(September 2015)</small><ref name="AR2014-15c">{{cite web |url=http://www.wincor-nixdorf.com/static/finanzberichte/2014-2015/q4/en/at-a-glance/key-figures.html |title=Annual Report 2014/15 |accessdate=May 30, 2016 |publisher=Wincor Nixdorf}}</ref> | homepage = [http://www.wincor-nixdorf.com www.wincor-nixdorf.com] }} '''Wincor Nixdorf ''' was a German corporation that provided retail and retail banking hardware, software, and services. Wincor Nixdorf was engaged primarily in the sale, manufacture, installation and service of self-service transaction systems (such as [[Automatic Teller Machine|ATM]]s), retail banking equipment, lottery terminals, postal terminals, software and services for global financial and commercial markets. On August 15, 2016, through the merger of Wincor Nixdorf and [[Diebold Inc.]], [[Diebold Nixdorf]] was formed as an international technology and services company.<ref name="unvesillogo">{{cite news| title =Newly combined Diebold Nixdorf unveils logo| url =http://www.ohio.com/business/newly-combined-diebold-nixdorf-unveils-logo-1.705182| publisher =Ohio.com| date =August 16, 2016| accessdate = 2016-09-14}}</ref>
==History== Founded by [[Heinz Nixdorf]], [[Nixdorf Computer]] was formed in 1952. In 1990 the company was purchased by [[Siemens AG]] and renamed [[Siemens Nixdorf Informationssysteme]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/01/11/business/company-news-siemens-buying-51-of-nixdorf.html|title=Siemens Buying 51% Of Nixdorf|last=Protzman|first=Ferdinand|date=|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en}}</ref> The company was re-focused exclusively on its current product set in 1998 and renamed '''Siemens Nixdorf Retail and Banking Systems [[GmbH]]'''. Following a buyout by [[Kohlberg Kravis Roberts]] and [[Goldman Sachs Capital Partners]] on October 1, 1999, the company was renamed Wincor Nixdorf. The company was taken public May 19, 2004 with a successful [[IPO]]. On November 8, 2006, Chief Executive Officer [[Karl-Heinz Stiller]] announced his resignation from the Board of Directors. Eckard Heidloff was elected as his replacement.<ref>[http://atmmarketplace.com/article.php?id=8026 BREAKING: Stiller steps down, Heidloff named Wincor's new CEO]atmmarketplace.com Nov 8, 2006. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211061121/http://www.atmmarketplace.com/article.php?id=8026 |date=February 11, 2007 }}</ref>
==Corporate relationships==
===IBM=== Following the end of the [[Diebold|InterBold]] partnership in 1997, [[IBM]] eventually entered into a re-distribution arrangement with Wincor Nixdorf. IBM sells and services Wincor Nixdorf machinery in several countries in the Americas.<ref>[http://www.wincor-nixdorf.com/internet/com/press/Archive/2001Archive/WincorIBM-2001/MultiChannel.html Wincor Nixdorf Germany<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
===Unisys=== [[Unisys]] also has a relationship with Wincor Nixdorf in some Latin American countries such as [[Brazil]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}
== Security issue == On July 12, 2016, the media reported that at least 34 [[Cash machine|ATM]]<nowiki/>s belonging to the Taiwanese {{ill|First Commercial Bank (Taiwan)|zh|第一商業銀行|lt=First Commercial Bank}} had been hacked via a [[Malware]] heist. Over 70 million [[New Taiwan dollar|Taiwan dollar]] (equivalent to 2 million [[United States dollar|USD]]) had been withdrawn illegally. The ATMs had been manufactured by Wincor Nixdorf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/national/national-news/2016/07/12/472025/Suspect-flees.htm|title=Suspect flees Taiwan after NT$70 million stolen from ATMs: police|access-date=2016-07-18}}</ref> According to the investigative authority, the international criminal hacker group used mobile devices instead of bank cards to activate the cash-withdrawal process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/biz/archives/2016/07/16/2003651099|title=ATM heist not an inside job: First Commercial Bank - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2016-07-18}}</ref> Security experts from the company were sent to investigate the security breach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/07/14/news/bank-atm-heist-taiwan/index.html|title=Taiwan bank ATMs spew out millions after hack|last=Kottasova|first=Ivana|date=2016-07-14|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2016-07-18}}</ref> At the time of the incident, there were approximately one thousand cash machines of this same type in use in Taiwan. A detailed investigation into the vulnerability began immediately.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-taiwan-banks-theft-idUSKCN0ZT0Y6|title=Taiwan seeks two Russian suspects in $2 million ATM malware heist|date=2016-07-13|newspaper=Reuters|access-date=2016-07-18}}</ref>
On July 17, 2016, Taiwanese authorities declared the case to be solved. The hacker group was found to consist of 16 people from [[Russia]], [[Romania]], and [[Latvia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/07/17/taiwan-atm-cyber-robbery-arrest/|title=Taiwan says foreign suspects arrested over $2 million ATM cyber robbery|date=2016-07-17|website=Fortune|access-date=2016-07-18}}</ref>
